[49m[39m    1,   1[0m:[39m[49m # Recipe 6.8: Disease Subtype Discovery
[0m[49m[39m    2,   2[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m-   3     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Innovation · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2.00–$8.00 per patient in the analysis cohort (depending on feature dimensionality and compute requirements)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+        3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Innovation · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2.00-$8.00 per patient in the analysis cohort (depending on feature dimensionality and compute requirements)
[0m[49m[39m    4,   4[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    5,   5[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m    6,   6[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    7,   7[0m:[39m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[39m    8,   8[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    9,   9[0m:[39m[49m A health system has 14,000 patients with a diagnosis of heart failure. They're all coded HFrEF or HFpEF. They all get guideline-directed medical therapy. And yet: some respond beautifully to beta-blockers while others don't. Some progress to transplant evaluation within two years while others remain stable for a decade. Some have readmission rates of 40% while others never come back.
[0m[49m[39m   10,  10[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   11,  11[0m:[39m[49m The clinical intuition is obvious: "heart failure" is not one disease. It's a collection of diseases that happen to share a final common pathway (the heart can't pump effectively). Cardiologists know this. They talk about ischemic vs. non-ischemic, about infiltrative cardiomyopathies, about hypertensive heart disease. But the current taxonomy is based on mechanism of injury and ejection fraction. It doesn't capture the full heterogeneity of how these patients actually behave.
[0m[49m[39m   12,  12[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   13,  13[0m:[39m[49m This isn't unique to heart failure. Type 2 diabetes, COPD, depression, sepsis, asthma, Parkinson's disease: all of these are "umbrella diagnoses" that likely contain distinct biological subtypes with different trajectories and different optimal treatments. A landmark 2018 study (Ahlqvist et al., The Lancet Diabetes & Endocrinology) identified five distinct clusters within Type 2 diabetes, each with different progression patterns and complication risks. That study used unsupervised clustering on six clinical variables across 8,980 patients. The subtypes they found predicted outcomes better than the traditional classification.
[0m[49m[39m   14,  14[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   15,  15[0m:[39m[49m The promise of disease subtype discovery is precision medicine at the population level. If you can identify that your 14,000 heart failure patients actually fall into six distinct phenotypic clusters, and that Cluster 3 responds poorly to standard beta-blocker therapy but responds well to SGLT2 inhibitors, you've just generated a hypothesis that could change treatment protocols. If Cluster 5 has a 60% readmission rate while the others average 15%, you've identified a group that needs intensive care management.
[0m[49m[39m   16,  16[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   17,  17[0m:[39m[49m The challenge: there are no labels. Nobody has pre-defined what the subtypes are. That's the whole point. You're using unsupervised learning to discover structure that the existing taxonomy doesn't capture. And that means you have no ground truth to validate against, no accuracy metric to optimize, and no way to know if the clusters you found are clinically meaningful until a physician looks at them and says "yes, these are real."
[0m[49m[39m   18,  18[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   19,  19[0m:[39m[49m This is research-grade work. It requires clinical collaboration from day one, rigorous statistical validation, and the intellectual honesty to admit when your clusters are artifacts of data quality rather than biology.
[0m[49m[39m   20,  20[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   21,  21[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A2 (HIGH). Add paragraph on IRB/ethics review requirements: research vs. QI classification, IRB timeline (4-12 weeks), and implication for the "Basic" implementation estimate. Disease subtype discovery using patient data typically requires IRB review before accessing real patient data. -->
[0m[49m[39m   22,  22[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   23,  23[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   24,  24[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   25,  25[0m:[39m[49m ## The Technology: How Unsupervised Clustering Discovers Disease Subtypes
[0m[49m[39m   26,  26[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   27,  27[0m:[39m[49m ### What Unsupervised Clustering Actually Does
[0m[49m[39m   28,  28[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   29,  29[0m:[39m[49m Let's start from first principles. Supervised learning has labels: you know the answer and you're training a model to predict it. Unsupervised clustering has no labels. You're handing the algorithm a pile of patient data and asking: "Are there natural groupings here that I haven't noticed?"
[0m[49m[39m   30,  30[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   31,  31[0m:[39m[49m The algorithm looks at each patient as a point in high-dimensional space. If you have 50 clinical features per patient (labs, vitals, medications, comorbidities, demographics), each patient is a point in 50-dimensional space. Clustering algorithms find regions of that space where patients are densely packed together and separated from other dense regions by relative emptiness.
[0m[49m[39m   32,  32[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   33,  33[0m:[39m[49m The intuition: if patients in one region of the space share similar lab patterns, similar medication responses, and similar outcomes, they might represent a coherent biological subtype. The "might" is doing a lot of work in that sentence, and we'll come back to it.
[0m[49m[39m   34,  34[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   35,  35[0m:[39m[49m ### The Feature Engineering Problem
[0m[49m[39m   36,  36[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   37,  37[0m:[39m[49m This is where disease subtype discovery diverges from standard clustering applications. In geographic clustering, your features are obvious (latitude, longitude). In disease subtype discovery, feature selection is the entire ballgame.
[0m[49m[39m   38,  38[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   39,  39[0m:[39m[49m Consider heart failure. What features might distinguish subtypes?
[0m[49m[39m   40,  40[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   41,  41[0m:[39m[49m **Clinical measurements:** Ejection fraction, BNP/NT-proBNP levels, troponin, creatinine, hemoglobin, sodium, potassium, liver function tests, thyroid function. Each measured at what time point? Baseline? Trajectory over time? Peak value? Rate of change?
[0m[49m[39m   42,  42[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   43,  43[0m:[39m[49m **Comorbidity profiles:** Diabetes, hypertension, atrial fibrillation, chronic kidney disease, COPD, obesity, sleep apnea, anemia. Binary presence/absence? Or severity-weighted?
[0m[49m[39m   44,  44[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   45,  45[0m:[39m[49m **Medication response:** Which drugs were tried? Which were tolerated? Which produced measurable improvement? This is retrospective observational data, not randomized trial data, so confounding is everywhere.
[0m[49m[39m   46,  46[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   47,  47[0m:[39m[49m **Functional status:** NYHA class, 6-minute walk distance, quality of life scores. Often sparsely documented.
[0m[49m[39m   48,  48[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   49,  49[0m:[39m[49m **Imaging features:** LV dimensions, wall motion abnormalities, valve disease, RV function. Requires structured extraction from echo reports.
[0m[49m[39m   50,  50[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   51,  51[0m:[39m[49m **Genomic data:** If available. Usually it's not, outside of research cohorts.
[0m[49m[39m   52,  52[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   53,  53[0m:[39m[49m The choices you make here determine what subtypes you can possibly find. If you only include lab values, you'll find lab-based subtypes. If you only include comorbidities, you'll find comorbidity-based subtypes. The subtypes are not "in the data" waiting to be discovered. They're a function of which data you choose to look at and how you represent it.
[0m[49m[39m   54,  54[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   55,  55[0m:[39m[49m This is why you absolutely need clinical collaboration from day one. A data scientist working alone will make feature choices that seem reasonable but miss clinically important distinctions. A cardiologist will tell you that the ratio of BNP to creatinine matters more than either value alone, or that the trajectory of ejection fraction over the first 90 days after diagnosis is more informative than the baseline value.
[0m[49m[39m   56,  56[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   57,  57[0m:[39m[49m ### Choosing a Clustering Algorithm
[0m[49m[39m   58,  58[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   59,  59[0m:[39m[49m There's no single "best" algorithm for disease subtype discovery. The choice depends on your assumptions about cluster shape, your tolerance for specifying the number of clusters in advance, and your data characteristics.
[0m[49m[39m   60,  60[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   61,  61[0m:[39m[49m **K-means** is the simplest and most widely used. It assumes clusters are roughly spherical (equal variance in all directions) and requires you to specify K (the number of clusters) in advance. It's fast, scales well, and produces interpretable results. Its weakness: real disease subtypes are rarely spherical in feature space. If one subtype is defined by a tight range of BNP values but a wide range of ejection fractions, K-means will struggle.
[0m[49m[39m   62,  62[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   63,  63[0m:[39m[49m **Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM)** generalize K-means by allowing elliptical clusters (different variances in different directions). They also provide soft assignments: instead of "this patient belongs to Cluster 3," you get "this patient has 72% probability of Cluster 3 and 28% probability of Cluster 1." That probabilistic assignment is clinically useful because many patients are genuinely on the boundary between subtypes.
[0m[49m[39m   64,  64[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   65,  65[0m:[39m[49m **Hierarchical clustering** builds a tree (dendrogram) of nested clusters, from individual patients up to the entire population. You can cut the tree at different levels to get different numbers of clusters. The advantage: you can visualize the full hierarchy and see which subtypes are "close" to each other. The disadvantage: it doesn't scale well beyond a few thousand patients without approximation methods.
[0m[49m[39m   66,  66[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   67,  67[0m:[39m[49m **DBSCAN and HDBSCAN** find clusters of arbitrary shape and automatically identify outliers (patients who don't fit any cluster). They don't require you to specify the number of clusters. The disadvantage: they're sensitive to their density parameters, and in high-dimensional clinical data, the concept of "density" becomes unreliable (the curse of dimensionality).
[0m[49m[39m   68,  68[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   69,  69[0m:[39m[49m **Spectral clustering** works by building a similarity graph between patients and finding communities in that graph. It handles non-convex cluster shapes well. It's computationally expensive for large populations but produces excellent results when the underlying structure is complex.
[0m[49m[39m   70,  70[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   71,  71[0m:[39m[49m **Consensus clustering** (also called ensemble clustering) runs multiple clustering algorithms (or the same algorithm with different parameters) and identifies groupings that are stable across runs. If patients consistently end up in the same cluster regardless of algorithm choice or random initialization, that's evidence the cluster is real rather than an artifact. This is the gold standard for disease subtype discovery in research settings.
[0m[49m[39m   72,  72[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   73,  73[0m:[39m[49m For a first pass, I'd recommend: run K-means, GMM, and hierarchical clustering across a range of K values (3 through 10). Use consensus clustering to identify which groupings are stable. Then validate the stable clusters clinically.
[0m[49m[39m   74,  74[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   75,  75[0m:[39m[49m ### Dimensionality Reduction
[0m[49m[39m   76,  76[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   77,  77[0m:[39m[49m If you have 50 or 100 clinical features, clustering directly in that space is problematic. The curse of dimensionality means that distance metrics become less meaningful as dimensions increase. Points that are "close" in 100-dimensional space may not be meaningfully similar.
[0m[49m[39m   78,  78[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   79,  79[0m:[39m[49m **PCA (Principal Component Analysis)** projects the data onto the directions of maximum variance. If 90% of the variance in your 50 features can be captured by 8 principal components, you can cluster in 8 dimensions instead of 50. The downside: principal components are linear combinations of original features, which makes them hard to interpret clinically. "PC3 = 0.4 * BNP + 0.3 * creatinine - 0.2 * ejection fraction" is not something a cardiologist can act on.
[0m[49m[39m   80,  80[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   81,  81[0m:[39m[49m **UMAP (Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection)** is a non-linear dimensionality reduction technique that preserves local structure. It's excellent for visualization (projecting patients into 2D for plotting) and can reveal cluster structure that PCA misses. But it's stochastic (different runs produce different layouts) and the distances in UMAP space are not directly interpretable.
[0m[49m[39m   82,  82[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   83,  83[0m:[39m[49m **Autoencoders** (neural network-based dimensionality reduction) learn a compressed representation of the patient data. They can capture non-linear relationships that PCA misses. The latent space of an autoencoder can be used as input to clustering. The downside: they're black boxes, and explaining why two patients ended up in the same cluster becomes harder.
[0m[49m[39m   84,  84[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   85,  85[0m:[39m[49m For disease subtype discovery, I'd recommend: use PCA for initial exploration and to determine how many dimensions carry meaningful variance. Use UMAP for visualization. Cluster in the PCA-reduced space (or the original space if dimensionality is manageable). Use the UMAP visualization to sanity-check whether the clusters look coherent.
[0m[49m[39m   86,  86[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   87,  87[0m:[39m[49m ### Validation: The Hard Part
[0m[49m[39m   88,  88[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   89,  89[0m:[39m[49m Here's the fundamental challenge of unsupervised disease subtype discovery: how do you know the clusters are real?
[0m[49m[39m   90,  90[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   91,  91[0m:[39m[49m **Internal validation metrics** tell you whether your clusters are well-formed, without needing external labels to compare against:
[0m[49m[39m   92,  92[0m:[39m[49m - Silhouette score: How similar is each patient to their own cluster vs. the nearest other cluster? Ranges from -1 to 1; higher is better.
[0m[49m[39m   93,  93[0m:[39m[49m - Calinski-Harabasz index: Ratio of between-cluster variance to within-cluster variance. Higher means more separated clusters.
[0m[49m[39m   94,  94[0m:[39m[49m - Davies-Bouldin index: Average similarity between each cluster and its most similar cluster. Lower is better.
[0m[49m[39m   95,  95[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   96,  96[0m:[39m[49m These metrics tell you whether the clusters are well-separated in feature space. They do not tell you whether the clusters are clinically meaningful. A clustering that perfectly separates patients by age and sex will have excellent internal metrics but zero clinical novelty.
[0m[49m[39m   97,  97[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   98,  98[0m:[39m[49m **Stability validation** tests whether the clusters are robust:
[0m[49m[39m   99,  99[0m:[39m[49m - Bootstrap resampling: Resample patients with replacement, re-cluster, and measure how often the same patients end up together. Stable clusters survive resampling.
[0m[49m[39m  100, 100[0m:[39m[49m - Feature perturbation: Add noise to features or drop features and re-cluster. Robust clusters survive perturbation.
[0m[49m[39m  101, 101[0m:[39m[49m - Algorithm variation: Do different algorithms find the same groupings? Consensus clustering formalizes this.
[0m[49m[39m  102, 102[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  103, 103[0m:[39m[49m **Clinical validation** is the only validation that ultimately matters:
[0m[49m[39m  104, 104[0m:[39m[49m - Do the clusters have different outcomes (mortality, readmission, progression)?
[0m[49m[39m  105, 105[0m:[39m[49m - Do the clusters have different treatment responses?
[0m[49m[39m  106, 106[0m:[39m[49m - Can a clinician look at the cluster profiles and say "yes, I recognize these patients"?
[0m[49m[39m  107, 107[0m:[39m[49m - Do the clusters suggest actionable differences in care?
[0m[49m[39m  108, 108[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  109, 109[0m:[39m[49m If your clusters have beautiful silhouette scores but identical outcomes across groups, they're not clinically useful subtypes. If they have mediocre silhouette scores but dramatically different 5-year mortality rates, they might be the most important finding in your dataset.
[0m[49m[39m  110, 110[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  111, 111[0m:[39m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[39m  112, 112[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  113, 113[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  114, 114[0m:[39m[49m [Cohort Definition] → [Feature Extraction] → [Preprocessing] → [Dimensionality Reduction]
[0m[49m[39m  115, 115[0m:[39m[49m     → [Multi-Algorithm Clustering] → [Consensus/Stability Analysis]
[0m[49m[39m  116, 116[0m:[39m[49m     → [Clinical Validation] → [Subtype Characterization] → [Deployment/Monitoring]
[0m[49m[39m  117, 117[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  118, 118[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  119, 119[0m:[39m[49m **Cohort definition:** Select the patient population. All patients with a specific diagnosis code? Only those with sufficient data completeness? Only those with a minimum follow-up period? These choices affect what subtypes you can find.
[0m[49m[39m  120, 120[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  121, 121[0m:[39m[49m **Feature extraction:** Pull clinical features from EHR data. This requires joining across multiple data domains (labs, medications, diagnoses, procedures, notes). Handle missingness explicitly: impute, exclude, or use algorithms that handle missing data natively.
[0m[49m[39m  122, 122[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  123, 123[0m:[39m[49m **Preprocessing:** Normalize features to comparable scales. Handle outliers. Encode categorical variables. This step has outsized impact on results because clustering algorithms are sensitive to feature scaling.
[0m[49m[39m  124, 124[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  125, 125[0m:[39m[49m **Dimensionality reduction:** Reduce feature space to a manageable number of dimensions while preserving meaningful variance.
[0m[49m[39m  126, 126[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  127, 127[0m:[39m[49m **Multi-algorithm clustering:** Run multiple algorithms across multiple K values. Don't commit to a single algorithm or a single K.
[0m[49m[39m  128, 128[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  129, 129[0m:[39m[49m **Consensus/stability analysis:** Identify which groupings are robust across algorithms, initializations, and resampling.
[0m[49m[39m  130, 130[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  131, 131[0m:[39m[49m **Clinical validation:** Evaluate discovered clusters against outcomes, treatment responses, and clinical interpretability. This is a human-in-the-loop step that cannot be automated.
[0m[49m[39m  132, 132[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  133, 133[0m:[39m[49m **Subtype characterization:** For validated clusters, describe the defining features in clinically actionable terms. "Cluster 3 is characterized by preserved ejection fraction, elevated BNP, high comorbidity burden (diabetes + CKD), and poor response to beta-blockers" is actionable. "Cluster 3 has high values on PC2" is not.
[0m[49m[39m  134, 134[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  135, 135[0m:[39m[49m **Deployment/monitoring:** If subtypes are validated and actionable, build a classifier that assigns new patients to discovered subtypes. Monitor for drift as the patient population changes over time.
[0m[49m[39m  136, 136[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  137, 137[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  138, 138[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  139, 139[0m:[39m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[39m  140, 140[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  141, 141[0m:[39m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[39m  142, 142[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  143, 143[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for ML compute and experimentation.** Disease subtype discovery is inherently iterative. You'll run dozens of clustering experiments with different feature sets, algorithms, and parameters before finding stable, clinically meaningful subtypes. SageMaker provides managed Jupyter notebooks for exploration, built-in implementations of K-means and PCA, and the ability to bring custom algorithms (GMM, HDBSCAN, consensus clustering) in containers. The experiment tracking in SageMaker Experiments lets you compare runs systematically rather than losing track of which parameter combination produced which result.
[0m[49m[39m  144, 144[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  145, 145[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S2 (MEDIUM). Add note on SageMaker notebook hardening for research workloads: recommend SageMaker Studio with domain-level VPC config, disable root access on notebook instances, use lifecycle configurations to restrict pip/conda to approved package mirrors, and enable notebook audit logging. Research workflows with interactive PHI access have higher risk than automated pipelines. -->
[0m[49m[39m  146, 146[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  147, 147[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon S3 for data lake storage.** The feature extraction pipeline pulls from multiple source systems (labs, medications, diagnoses, notes) and materializes a patient-feature matrix that may be hundreds of megabytes to several gigabytes. S3 provides durable, encrypted storage for both the raw extracted features and the intermediate/final clustering results. Versioning lets you reproduce any analysis from any point in time.
[0m[49m[39m  148, 148[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  149, 149[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S3 (MEDIUM). Add note on data retention: implement S3 lifecycle policies for experiment artifacts (transition to Glacier after retention period, delete after maximum retention). Maintain a manifest of patient IDs per experiment to support HIPAA amendment and accounting-of-disclosures requests. -->
[0m[49m[39m  150, 150[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  151, 151[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Glue for ETL and feature extraction.** Building the patient-feature matrix requires joining across multiple data domains, handling temporal logic (which lab value to use when there are multiple?), and applying business rules (how to encode medication history). Glue's Spark-based ETL handles this at scale, and the Glue Data Catalog provides schema management for the feature tables.
[0m[49m[39m  152, 152[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  153, 153[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon Athena for ad-hoc exploration.** Before committing to a feature set, you need to explore the data: check distributions, identify missingness patterns, understand correlations. Athena lets you query the feature tables in S3 with standard SQL without provisioning any infrastructure.
[0m[49m[39m  154, 154[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  155, 155[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for subtype assignment storage.** Once subtypes are validated and a classifier is built, new patients need to be assigned to subtypes in real time. DynamoDB provides low-latency lookups by patient ID for downstream systems (care management platforms, clinical decision support) that need to know a patient's subtype.
[0m[49m[39m  156, 156[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  157, 157[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Step Functions for pipeline orchestration.** The full pipeline (extract features, preprocess, reduce dimensions, cluster, validate, characterize) has multiple stages with dependencies. Step Functions orchestrates this as a state machine with error handling, retries, and audit logging. The clinical validation step uses Step Functions' callback pattern (`.waitForTaskToken`): the state machine pauses, sends a notification to the clinical review team with the cluster characterization report, and resumes when the clinician approves or requests re-analysis with different parameters.
[0m[49m[39m  158, 158[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  159, 159[0m:[39m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[39m  160, 160[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  161, 161[0m:[39m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[39m  162, 162[0m:[39m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[39m  163, 163[0m:[39m[49m     A[EHR Data Sources\nLabs, Meds, Dx, Notes] -->|Glue ETL| B[S3 Data Lake\nPatient Feature Matrix]
[0m[49m[39m  164, 164[0m:[39m[49m     B -->|Athena| C[Exploratory Analysis\nFeature Selection]
[0m[49m[39m  165, 165[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Refined Features| D[SageMaker\nPreprocessing + PCA]
[0m[49m[39m  166, 166[0m:[39m[49m     D --> E[SageMaker\nMulti-Algorithm Clustering]
[0m[49m[39m  167, 167[0m:[39m[49m     E --> F[SageMaker\nConsensus + Stability Analysis]
[0m[49m[39m  168, 168[0m:[39m[49m     F --> G[Clinical Validation\nHuman-in-the-Loop]
[0m[49m[39m  169, 169[0m:[39m[49m     G -->|Validated Subtypes| H[SageMaker\nSubtype Classifier Training]
[0m[49m[39m  170, 170[0m:[39m[49m     H --> I[SageMaker Endpoint\nReal-Time Assignment]
[0m[49m[39m  171, 171[0m:[39m[49m     I --> J[DynamoDB\nPatient Subtype Store]
[0m[49m[39m  172, 172[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  173, 173[0m:[39m[49m     K[Step Functions] -.->|Orchestrates| B
[0m[49m[39m  174, 174[0m:[39m[49m     K -.-> D
[0m[49m[39m  175, 175[0m:[39m[49m     K -.-> E
[0m[49m[39m  176, 176[0m:[39m[49m     K -.-> F
[0m[49m[39m  177, 177[0m:[39m[49m     K -.-> H
[0m[49m[39m  178, 178[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  179, 179[0m:[39m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  180, 180[0m:[39m[49m     style E fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  181, 181[0m:[39m[49m     style G fill:#9f9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  182, 182[0m:[39m[49m     style J fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  183, 183[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  184, 184[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  185, 185[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  186, 186[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  187, 187[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  188, 188[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  189, 189[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon Athena, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Step Functions, AWS KMS |
[0m[49m[39m  190, 190[0m:[39m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:CreateEndpoint`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `athena:StartQueryExecution`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `states:StartExecution`. Scope all permissions to specific resource ARNs (e.g., `s3:GetObject` on `arn:aws:s3:::patient-features-bucket/cohort-*`). |
[0m[49m[39m  191, 191[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (patient clinical data is PHI) |
[0m[49m[39m  192, 192[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; SageMaker: KMS-encrypted volumes and endpoints; Glue: KMS for job bookmarks and temp storage; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[39m  193, 193[0m:[39m[49m | **VPC** | SageMaker notebooks and training jobs in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, and SageMaker API. No internet egress for PHI workloads. Configure Glue connections with VPC subnet and security group for jobs accessing VPC-resident data sources (EHR databases, data warehouses). |
[0m[49m[39m  194, 194[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all service API calls. SageMaker experiment tracking provides additional audit of model lineage. |
[0m[49m[39m  195, 195[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic patient cohort with clinical features. MIMIC-IV (PhysioNet) provides realistic ICU patient data for development. Never use real PHI in dev/research without IRB approval. |
[0m[49m[39m  196, 196[0m:[39m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Glue ETL: ~$0.44/DPU-hour. SageMaker ml.m5.xlarge notebook: ~$0.23/hr. Training jobs (ml.m5.4xlarge): ~$0.92/hr. Expect 20-50 hours of compute for a full exploration cycle. |
[0m[49m[39m  197, 197[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  198, 198[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  199, 199[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  200, 200[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  201, 201[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  202, 202[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | ML experimentation, clustering algorithms, model training, real-time inference endpoint |
[0m[49m[39m  203, 203[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores patient feature matrices, intermediate results, model artifacts, and cluster characterizations |
[0m[49m[39m  204, 204[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL pipeline to extract and join clinical features from source systems into patient-feature matrix |
[0m[49m[39m  205, 205[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Athena** | SQL-based exploration of feature distributions, missingness, and correlations |
[0m[49m[39m  206, 206[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Low-latency storage of patient subtype assignments for downstream consumption |
[0m[49m[39m  207, 207[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates the multi-stage pipeline with error handling and audit trail |
[0m[49m[39m  208, 208[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest |
[0m[49m[39m  209, 209[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring, logging, and alerting for pipeline health and drift detection |
[0m[49m[39m  210, 210[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  211, 211[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  212, 212[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  213, 213[0m:[39m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[39m  214, 214[0m:[39m[49m >
[0m[49m[39m  215, 215[0m:[39m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-examples`](https://github.com/aws/amazon-sagemaker-examples): Comprehensive SageMaker examples including built-in K-means, PCA, and custom algorithm containers
[0m[49m[39m  216, 216[0m:[39m[49m > - [`aws-healthcare-lifescience-ai-ml`](https://github.com/aws-samples/aws-healthcare-lifescience-ai-ml): Healthcare-specific ML examples on AWS including patient cohort analysis patterns
[0m[49m[39m  217, 217[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  218, 218[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  219, 219[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 220     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 1: Define the cohort.** Before any clustering happens, you need a clean, well-defined patient population. This means selecting patients with the target diagnosis, applying minimum data completeness thresholds, and defining the observation window. A cohort with 40% missing lab values will produce clusters driven by missingness patterns rather than biology. This step also handles temporal alignment: for each patient, define a "index date" (diagnosis date, first encounter, etc.) and extract features relative to that anchor. Skip this step and your clusters will reflect data availability rather than disease biology.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Define the cohort.** Before any clustering happens, you need a clean, well-defined patient population. This means selecting patients with the target diagnosis, applying minimum data completeness thresholds, and defining the observation window. A cohort with 40% missing lab values will produce clusters driven by missingness patterns rather than biology. This step also handles temporal alignment: for each patient, define an "index date" (diagnosis date, first encounter, etc.) and extract features relative to that anchor. Skip this step and your clusters will reflect data availability rather than disease biology.
[0m[49m[39m  221, 221[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  222, 222[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  223, 223[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION define_cohort(diagnosis_codes, min_data_completeness, observation_window):
[0m[49m[39m  224, 224[0m:[39m[49m     // Select all patients with the target diagnosis within the study period.
[0m[49m[39m  225, 225[0m:[39m[49m     // diagnosis_codes: list of ICD-10 codes defining the disease (e.g., I50.x for heart failure)
[0m[49m[39m  226, 226[0m:[39m[49m     // min_data_completeness: minimum fraction of required features that must be non-null (e.g., 0.7)
[0m[49m[39m  227, 227[0m:[39m[49m     // observation_window: how far back/forward from index date to look for features (e.g., 365 days)
[0m[49m[39m  228, 228[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  229, 229[0m:[39m[49m     candidates = query patients WHERE any diagnosis IN diagnosis_codes
[0m[49m[39m  230, 230[0m:[39m[49m                  AND diagnosis_date BETWEEN study_start AND study_end
[0m[49m[39m  231, 231[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  232, 232[0m:[39m[49m     // For each candidate, determine their index date (first qualifying diagnosis)
[0m[49m[39m  233, 233[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient in candidates:
[0m[49m[39m  234, 234[0m:[39m[49m         patient.index_date = earliest date of qualifying diagnosis
[0m[49m[39m  235, 235[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  236, 236[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply data completeness filter
[0m[49m[39m  237, 237[0m:[39m[49m     // Patients with too much missing data will create clusters based on missingness, not biology
[0m[49m[39m  238, 238[0m:[39m[49m     eligible = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  239, 239[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient in candidates:
[0m[49m[39m  240, 240[0m:[39m[49m         completeness = count_non_null_features(patient, observation_window) / total_required_features
[0m[49m[39m  241, 241[0m:[39m[49m         IF completeness >= min_data_completeness:
[0m[49m[39m  242, 242[0m:[39m[49m             append patient to eligible
[0m[49m[39m  243, 243[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  244, 244[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN eligible  // The analysis cohort, with index dates assigned
[0m[49m[39m  245, 245[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  246, 246[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  247, 247[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Extract and engineer features.** This is where clinical expertise matters most. You're building a numerical representation of each patient that captures the dimensions along which subtypes might differ. For each patient, extract labs (using the value closest to index date, or the median over the observation window), medications (binary indicators or duration-weighted), comorbidities (binary or severity-scored), vitals, and any other relevant structured data. Feature engineering choices here directly determine what subtypes you can discover.
[0m[49m[39m  248, 248[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  249, 249[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  250, 250[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_features(cohort, feature_config):
[0m[49m[39m  251, 251[0m:[39m[49m     // feature_config defines which features to extract and how to summarize them.
[0m[49m[39m  252, 252[0m:[39m[49m     // Example config entry: { name: "bnp_baseline", source: "labs", loinc: "42637-9",
[0m[49m[39m  253, 253[0m:[39m[49m     //                         aggregation: "closest_to_index", window: "90_days_before" }
[0m[49m[39m  254, 254[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  255, 255[0m:[39m[49m     feature_matrix = empty matrix (rows = patients, columns = features)
[0m[49m[39m  256, 256[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  257, 257[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient in cohort:
[0m[49m[39m  258, 258[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each feature_def in feature_config:
[0m[49m[39m  259, 259[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  260, 260[0m:[39m[49m             IF feature_def.source == "labs":
[0m[49m[39m  261, 261[0m:[39m[49m                 // Pull lab values within the specified window relative to index date
[0m[49m[39m  262, 262[0m:[39m[49m                 values = get_lab_values(patient, feature_def.loinc,
[0m[49m[39m  263, 263[0m:[39m[49m                                         patient.index_date, feature_def.window)
[0m[49m[39m  264, 264[0m:[39m[49m                 // Apply aggregation: closest_to_index, median, max, slope, etc.
[0m[49m[39m  265, 265[0m:[39m[49m                 feature_matrix[patient][feature_def.name] = aggregate(values, feature_def.aggregation)
[0m[49m[39m  266, 266[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  267, 267[0m:[39m[49m             ELSE IF feature_def.source == "medications":
[0m[49m[39m  268, 268[0m:[39m[49m                 // Check if patient was on this medication class during the window
[0m[49m[39m  269, 269[0m:[39m[49m                 // Can be binary (on/off) or continuous (days on therapy)
[0m[49m[39m  270, 270[0m:[39m[49m                 feature_matrix[patient][feature_def.name] = get_medication_exposure(
[0m[49m[39m  271, 271[0m:[39m[49m                     patient, feature_def.drug_class, patient.index_date, feature_def.window)
[0m[49m[39m  272, 272[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  273, 273[0m:[39m[49m             ELSE IF feature_def.source == "diagnoses":
[0m[49m[39m  274, 274[0m:[39m[49m                 // Check for presence of comorbidity codes
[0m[49m[39m  275, 275[0m:[39m[49m                 feature_matrix[patient][feature_def.name] = has_diagnosis(
[0m[49m[39m  276, 276[0m:[39m[49m                     patient, feature_def.icd_codes, before_date=patient.index_date)
[0m[49m[39m  277, 277[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  278, 278[0m:[39m[49m             ELSE IF feature_def.source == "vitals":
[0m[49m[39m  279, 279[0m:[39m[49m                 values = get_vitals(patient, feature_def.vital_type,
[0m[49m[39m  280, 280[0m:[39m[49m                                     patient.index_date, feature_def.window)
[0m[49m[39m  281, 281[0m:[39m[49m                 feature_matrix[patient][feature_def.name] = aggregate(values, feature_def.aggregation)
[0m[49m[39m  282, 282[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  283, 283[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN feature_matrix
[0m[49m[39m  284, 284[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  285, 285[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  286, 286[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Preprocess and reduce dimensions.** Raw clinical features have wildly different scales (BNP ranges from 0 to 35,000 pg/mL; ejection fraction ranges from 5 to 75%). Without normalization, high-magnitude features dominate the distance calculations and clustering finds "BNP subtypes" rather than meaningful phenotypes. After scaling, apply PCA to identify how many dimensions carry meaningful variance and reduce the feature space accordingly. This step also handles remaining missing values through imputation.
[0m[49m[39m  287, 287[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  288, 288[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  289, 289[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION preprocess_and_reduce(feature_matrix, variance_threshold=0.90):
[0m[49m[39m  290, 290[0m:[39m[49m     // Step 3a: Handle remaining missing values
[0m[49m[39m  291, 291[0m:[39m[49m     // Multiple imputation is preferred for research; median imputation is acceptable for exploration
[0m[49m[39m  292, 292[0m:[39m[49m     imputed_matrix = impute_missing(feature_matrix, method="iterative")
[0m[49m[39m  293, 293[0m:[39m[49m     // "iterative" = MICE (Multiple Imputation by Chained Equations)
[0m[49m[39m  294, 294[0m:[39m[49m     // Each missing value is predicted from the other features, iteratively
[0m[49m[39m  295, 295[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  296, 296[0m:[39m[49m     // Step 3b: Standardize all features to zero mean, unit variance
[0m[49m[39m  297, 297[0m:[39m[49m     // Without this, features measured in large units (BNP: 0-35000) dominate
[0m[49m[39m  298, 298[0m:[39m[49m     // features measured in small units (creatinine: 0.5-15.0)
[0m[49m[39m  299, 299[0m:[39m[49m     scaled_matrix = standardize(imputed_matrix)  // z-score normalization: (x - mean) / std
[0m[49m[39m  300, 300[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  301, 301[0m:[39m[49m     // Step 3c: PCA for dimensionality reduction
[0m[49m[39m  302, 302[0m:[39m[49m     // Determine how many components capture the specified fraction of total variance
[0m[49m[39m  303, 303[0m:[39m[49m     pca_model = fit_PCA(scaled_matrix)
[0m[49m[39m  304, 304[0m:[39m[49m     n_components = find_n_where_cumulative_variance >= variance_threshold
[0m[49m[39m  305, 305[0m:[39m[49m     // Typical result: 50 features reduce to 8-15 principal components capturing 90% of variance
[0m[49m[39m  306, 306[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  307, 307[0m:[39m[49m     reduced_matrix = transform(scaled_matrix, pca_model, n_components)
[0m[49m[39m  308, 308[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  309, 309[0m:[39m[49m     // Step 3d: Also generate UMAP embedding for visualization (2D)
[0m[49m[39m  310, 310[0m:[39m[49m     umap_embedding = fit_UMAP(scaled_matrix, n_components=2)
[0m[49m[39m  311, 311[0m:[39m[49m     // UMAP is for visualization only; clustering happens in PCA space
[0m[49m[39m  312, 312[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  313, 313[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN reduced_matrix, pca_model, umap_embedding, scaled_matrix
[0m[49m[39m  314, 314[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  315, 315[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  316, 316[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Run multi-algorithm clustering.** Don't bet on a single algorithm or a single K. Run K-means, GMM, and hierarchical clustering across K=2 through K=10. For each combination, record the cluster assignments and internal validation metrics. This gives you a landscape of possible groupings rather than a single answer. The goal is to identify values of K and algorithm choices where the results converge, suggesting genuine structure rather than algorithmic artifacts.
[0m[49m[39m  317, 317[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  318, 318[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  319, 319[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION run_multi_algorithm_clustering(reduced_matrix, k_range=[2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,10]):
[0m[49m[39m  320, 320[0m:[39m[49m     // Store all results for comparison
[0m[49m[39m  321, 321[0m:[39m[49m     all_results = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  322, 322[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  323, 323[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each k in k_range:
[0m[49m[39m  324, 324[0m:[39m[49m         // K-means: fast, assumes spherical clusters
[0m[49m[39m  325, 325[0m:[39m[49m         kmeans_labels = fit_KMeans(reduced_matrix, n_clusters=k)
[0m[49m[39m  326, 326[0m:[39m[49m         kmeans_silhouette = compute_silhouette_score(reduced_matrix, kmeans_labels)
[0m[49m[39m  327, 327[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  328, 328[0m:[39m[49m         // Gaussian Mixture Model: allows elliptical clusters, provides probabilities
[0m[49m[39m  329, 329[0m:[39m[49m         gmm_labels = fit_GMM(reduced_matrix, n_components=k)
[0m[49m[39m  330, 330[0m:[39m[49m         gmm_bic = compute_BIC(reduced_matrix, gmm_model)  // lower BIC = better fit/complexity tradeoff
[0m[49m[39m  331, 331[0m:[39m[49m         gmm_silhouette = compute_silhouette_score(reduced_matrix, gmm_labels)
[0m[49m[39m  332, 332[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  333, 333[0m:[39m[49m         // Hierarchical (Ward linkage): builds dendrogram, cut at k clusters
[0m[49m[39m  334, 334[0m:[39m[49m         hier_labels = fit_hierarchical(reduced_matrix, n_clusters=k, linkage="ward")
[0m[49m[39m  335, 335[0m:[39m[49m         hier_silhouette = compute_silhouette_score(reduced_matrix, hier_labels)
[0m[49m[39m  336, 336[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  337, 337[0m:[39m[49m         append to all_results: {
[0m[49m[39m  338, 338[0m:[39m[49m             k: k,
[0m[49m[39m  339, 339[0m:[39m[49m             algorithms: {
[0m[49m[39m  340, 340[0m:[39m[49m                 "kmeans": { labels: kmeans_labels, silhouette: kmeans_silhouette },
[0m[49m[39m  341, 341[0m:[39m[49m                 "gmm":    { labels: gmm_labels, silhouette: gmm_silhouette, bic: gmm_bic },
[0m[49m[39m  342, 342[0m:[39m[49m                 "hierarchical": { labels: hier_labels, silhouette: hier_silhouette }
[0m[49m[39m  343, 343[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  344, 344[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  345, 345[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  346, 346[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN all_results
[0m[49m[39m  347, 347[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  348, 348[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  349, 349[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Consensus clustering and stability analysis.** This is where you separate signal from noise. Run the clustering 100+ times with bootstrap resampling (randomly sampling 80% of patients each time) and track how often each pair of patients ends up in the same cluster. Build a consensus matrix: entry (i,j) is the fraction of runs where patient i and patient j were co-clustered. Cluster the consensus matrix itself to find the final stable groupings. Patients who consistently cluster together across resamples are genuinely similar; patients who bounce between clusters are on the boundary.
[0m[49m[39m  350, 350[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  351, 351[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  352, 352[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION consensus_clustering(scaled_matrix, k, n_iterations=100, subsample_fraction=0.8):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // We use the full scaled feature space here rather than PCA-reduced space.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Bootstrap resampling provides implicit regularization, and retaining all features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // ensures the consensus matrix captures the full phenotypic similarity structure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  353, 357[0m:[39m[49m     // consensus_matrix[i][j] = fraction of times patient i and j were in the same cluster
[0m[49m[39m  354, 358[0m:[39m[49m     n_patients = number of rows in scaled_matrix
[0m[49m[39m  355, 359[0m:[39m[49m     co_cluster_count = zero matrix (n_patients x n_patients)
[0m[49m[39m  356, 360[0m:[39m[49m     co_occurrence_count = zero matrix (n_patients x n_patients)  // times both were sampled
[0m[49m[39m  357, 361[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  358, 362[0m:[39m[49m     FOR iteration = 1 to n_iterations:
[0m[49m[39m  359, 363[0m:[39m[49m         // Subsample 80% of patients (bootstrap)
[0m[49m[39m  360, 364[0m:[39m[49m         sampled_indices = random_sample(n_patients, fraction=subsample_fraction)
[0m[49m[39m  361, 365[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  362, 366[0m:[39m[49m         // Cluster the subsample
[0m[49m[39m  363, 367[0m:[39m[49m         subsample = scaled_matrix[sampled_indices]
[0m[49m[39m  364, 368[0m:[39m[49m         labels = fit_KMeans(subsample, n_clusters=k)  // or rotate algorithms across iterations
[0m[49m[39m  365, 369[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  366, 370[0m:[39m[49m         // Update co-clustering counts
[0m[49m[39m  367, 371[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each pair (i, j) in sampled_indices:
[0m[49m[39m  368, 372[0m:[39m[49m             co_occurrence_count[i][j] += 1
[0m[49m[39m  369, 373[0m:[39m[49m             IF labels[i] == labels[j]:
[0m[49m[39m  370, 374[0m:[39m[49m                 co_cluster_count[i][j] += 1
[0m[49m[39m  371, 375[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  372, 376[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute consensus matrix (fraction of co-occurrences where pair was co-clustered)
[0m[49m[39m  373, 377[0m:[39m[49m     consensus_matrix = co_cluster_count / co_occurrence_count
[0m[49m[39m  374, 378[0m:[39m[49m     // Values near 1.0 = always together. Values near 0.0 = never together.
[0m[49m[39m  375, 379[0m:[39m[49m     // Values near 0.5 = unstable assignment (boundary patients).
[0m[49m[39m  376, 380[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  377, 381[0m:[39m[49m     // Final clustering on the consensus matrix itself
[0m[49m[39m  378, 382[0m:[39m[49m     final_labels = fit_hierarchical(1 - consensus_matrix, n_clusters=k, linkage="average")
[0m[49m[39m  379, 383[0m:[39m[49m     // Using (1 - consensus) as a distance: patients always co-clustered have distance 0
[0m[49m[39m  380, 384[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  381, 385[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute cluster stability (proportion of ambiguous assignments)
[0m[49m[39m  382, 386[0m:[39m[49m     stability_scores = compute_PAC(consensus_matrix)  // Proportion of Ambiguous Clustering
[0m[49m[39m  383, 387[0m:[39m[49m     // PAC = fraction of consensus values between 0.1 and 0.9 (the "ambiguous zone")
[0m[49m[39m  384, 388[0m:[39m[49m     // Lower PAC = more stable clustering
[0m[49m[39m  385, 389[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  386, 390[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN final_labels, consensus_matrix, stability_scores
[0m[49m[39m  387, 391[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  388, 392[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  389, 393[0m:[39m[49m **Step 6: Clinical validation and characterization.** The clusters mean nothing until validated against outcomes. For each discovered subtype, compute outcome differences (mortality, readmission, disease progression), treatment response differences, and generate interpretable profiles. Present these to clinical domain experts for review. A cluster is clinically meaningful if: (a) it has distinct outcomes, (b) a clinician can recognize the phenotype, and (c) it suggests actionable differences in care.
[0m[49m[39m  390, 394[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  391, 395[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  392, 396[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION validate_and_characterize(cohort, feature_matrix, labels, outcomes_data):
[0m[49m[39m  393, 397[0m:[39m[49m     n_clusters = number of unique values in labels
[0m[49m[39m  394, 398[0m:[39m[49m     characterization = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  395, 399[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  396, 400[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each cluster_id in 0 to n_clusters-1:
[0m[49m[39m  397, 401[0m:[39m[49m         cluster_patients = cohort WHERE labels == cluster_id
[0m[49m[39m  398, 402[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  399, 403[0m:[39m[49m         // Outcome analysis: do clusters have different trajectories?
[0m[49m[39m  400, 404[0m:[39m[49m         mortality_rate = compute_mortality(cluster_patients, outcomes_data)
[0m[49m[39m  401, 405[0m:[39m[49m         readmission_rate = compute_30day_readmission(cluster_patients, outcomes_data)
[0m[49m[39m  402, 406[0m:[39m[49m         progression_rate = compute_disease_progression(cluster_patients, outcomes_data)
[0m[49m[39m  403, 407[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  404, 408[0m:[39m[49m         // Feature profile: what defines this cluster?
[0m[49m[39m  405, 409[0m:[39m[49m         // For each feature, compute mean/median for this cluster vs. overall population
[0m[49m[39m  406, 410[0m:[39m[49m         feature_profile = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  407, 411[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each feature in feature_matrix.columns:
[0m[49m[39m  408, 412[0m:[39m[49m             cluster_mean = mean(feature_matrix[cluster_patients][feature])
[0m[49m[39m  409, 413[0m:[39m[49m             overall_mean = mean(feature_matrix[feature])
[0m[49m[39m  410, 414[0m:[39m[49m             effect_size = (cluster_mean - overall_mean) / std(feature_matrix[feature])
[0m[49m[39m  411, 415[0m:[39m[49m             feature_profile[feature] = { cluster_mean, overall_mean, effect_size }
[0m[49m[39m  412, 416[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  413, 417[0m:[39m[49m         // Identify top distinguishing features (largest absolute effect sizes)
[0m[49m[39m  414, 418[0m:[39m[49m         top_features = sort feature_profile by absolute(effect_size), take top 10
[0m[49m[39m  415, 419[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  416, 420[0m:[39m[49m         // Statistical significance: are outcome differences real or chance?
[0m[49m[39m  417, 421[0m:[39m[49m         // Compare this cluster's outcomes to all other clusters combined
[0m[49m[39m  418, 422[0m:[39m[49m         outcome_p_values = compute_log_rank_test(cluster_patients, other_patients, outcomes_data)
[0m[49m[39m  419, 423[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  420, 424[0m:[39m[49m         characterization[cluster_id] = {
[0m[49m[39m  421, 425[0m:[39m[49m             size: count(cluster_patients),
[0m[49m[39m  422, 426[0m:[39m[49m             fraction: count(cluster_patients) / count(cohort),
[0m[49m[39m  423, 427[0m:[39m[49m             outcomes: { mortality_rate, readmission_rate, progression_rate },
[0m[49m[39m  424, 428[0m:[39m[49m             top_features: top_features,
[0m[49m[39m  425, 429[0m:[39m[49m             p_values: outcome_p_values
[0m[49m[39m  426, 430[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  427, 431[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  428, 432[0m:[39m[49m     // Generate summary report for clinical review
[0m[49m[39m  429, 433[0m:[39m[49m     report = format_clinical_report(characterization)
[0m[49m[39m  430, 434[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN characterization, report
[0m[49m[39m  431, 435[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  432, 436[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  433, 437[0m:[39m[49m **Step 7: Build subtype classifier for new patients.** Once subtypes are validated, you need a way to assign new patients to the discovered subtypes without re-running the full clustering pipeline.
[0m[49m[39m  434, 438[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  435, 439[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A1 (HIGH). Add subsection or expanded intro before Step 7 addressing the research-to-production transition: (1) prospective validation on a temporal holdout cohort, (2) FDA CDS considerations under 21st Century Cures Act, (3) clinical governance approval workflow, (4) drift monitoring strategy for deployed subtype classifier. -->
[0m[49m[39m  436, 440[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 437     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m Train a supervised classifier (random forest, gradient boosting) on the original cohort using the cluster labels as the target. This classifier can then be deployed as a real-time endpoint that takes a new patient's features and returns their predicted subtype.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Train a supervised classifier (random forest, gradient boosting) on the original cohort using the cluster labels as the target. This classifier can then be deployed as a real-time endpoint that takes a new patient's features and returns their predicted subtype. Consider adding a confidence threshold: if the maximum predicted probability is below 0.6, flag the patient as "unclassifiable" rather than forcing assignment to a subtype. These boundary patients may represent emerging subtypes not captured in the original discovery cohort.
[0m[49m[39m  438, 442[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  439, 443[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  440, 444[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION train_subtype_classifier(feature_matrix, validated_labels):
[0m[49m[39m  441, 445[0m:[39m[49m     // Split into train/test to estimate assignment accuracy
[0m[49m[39m  442, 446[0m:[39m[49m     train_features, test_features, train_labels, test_labels = split(
[0m[49m[39m  443, 447[0m:[39m[49m         feature_matrix, validated_labels, test_fraction=0.2, stratified=True)
[0m[49m[39m  444, 448[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  445, 449[0m:[39m[49m     // Train a gradient boosting classifier
[0m[49m[39m  446, 450[0m:[39m[49m     // Why gradient boosting? It handles mixed feature types well, provides feature importance,
[0m[49m[39m  447, 451[0m:[39m[49m     // and is robust to the moderate class imbalance typical in subtype discovery
[0m[49m[39m  448, 452[0m:[39m[49m     classifier = fit_GradientBoosting(
[0m[49m[39m  449, 453[0m:[39m[49m         train_features, train_labels,
[0m[49m[39m  450, 454[0m:[39m[49m         n_estimators=200,
[0m[49m[39m  451, 455[0m:[39m[49m         max_depth=5,
[0m[49m[39m  452, 456[0m:[39m[49m         learning_rate=0.1
[0m[49m[39m  453, 457[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  454, 458[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  455, 459[0m:[39m[49m     // Evaluate: how accurately can we assign patients to the discovered subtypes?
[0m[49m[39m  456, 460[0m:[39m[49m     test_predictions = classifier.predict(test_features)
[0m[49m[39m  457, 461[0m:[39m[49m     accuracy = compute_accuracy(test_labels, test_predictions)
[0m[49m[39m  458, 462[0m:[39m[49m     confusion = compute_confusion_matrix(test_labels, test_predictions)
[0m[49m[39m  459, 463[0m:[39m[49m     // Accuracy > 90% is typical for well-separated subtypes
[0m[49m[39m  460, 464[0m:[39m[49m     // Lower accuracy suggests overlapping subtypes (which is clinically realistic)
[0m[49m[39m  461, 465[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  462, 466[0m:[39m[49m     // Feature importance: which features drive subtype assignment?
[0m[49m[39m  463, 467[0m:[39m[49m     importance = classifier.feature_importances
[0m[49m[39m  464, 468[0m:[39m[49m     // This tells clinicians which measurements matter most for subtyping
[0m[49m[39m  465, 469[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  466, 470[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN classifier, accuracy, confusion, importance
[0m[49m[39m  467, 471[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  468, 472[0m:[39m[49m 
